* https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Root_system

Let E be a finite-dimensional Euclidean vector space, with the standard Euclidean inner product denoted by ( ‚ãÖ , ‚ãÖ ). A root system Œ¶ in E is a finite set of non-zero vectors (called roots) that satisfy the following conditions:[2][3]
  - The roots span E.
  - The only scalar multiples of a root Œ± ‚àà Œ¶ are Œ± itself and ‚àíŒ±
  - For every root Œ± ‚àà Œ¶, the set Œ¶  is closed under reflection through the hyperplane perpendicular to Œ±.
  - (Integrality) If Œ± and Œ≤ are roots in Œ¶, then the projection of Œ≤ onto the line through Œ± is an integer or half-integer multiple of Œ±.
An equivalent way of writing conditions 3 and 4 is as follows:
    For any two roots Œ± , Œ≤ ‚àà Œ¶ the set Œ¶ contains the element œÉ_Œ±(Œ≤):=Œ≤‚àí2(Œ±,Œ≤)/(Œ±,Œ±)Œ±.
    For any two roots Œ± , Œ≤ ‚àà Œ¶, the number ‚ü®Œ≤,Œ±‚ü© := 2(Œ±,Œ≤)/(Œ±,Œ±) is an integer.

The group of isometries of E generated by reflections through hyperplanes associated to the roots of Œ¶ is called the Weyl group of Œ¶

If g is a complex semisimple Lie algebra and h is a Cartan subalgebra [=maximal commutative subalgebra of g and if ad_H is diagonalizable for each H ‚àà h), we can construct a root system as follows. We say that Œ±‚ààh‚àó is a root of g relative to h if Œ± ‚â† 0 and there exists some X ‚â† 0 ‚àà g such that
    [H , X] = Œ±(H)X for all H ‚àà h

